{"blockStates":[{"name":"Control a Qubit with Rabi Oscillation","uid":"Sticker #17296c8d695","x":6,"y":5,"width":281,"height":528,"marginX":15,"marginY":15,"userText":"The Rabi oscillation can be used to operate a\nqubit with a laser. The trick is to generate a \nlight impulse of specific duration that targets \na specific state. When the oscillation starts at \nthe beginning of the impulse, the qubit will \nstart to rotate on the Bloch sphere. When the\noscillation stops, the qubit will end up in \nthe final state. This mechanism is used to\nmake the C-ROT gate, which is equivalent \nto the C-NOT gate in quantum circuits.\n\nThe way to control the final state is to specify\nthe duration of the impulse. The π-pulse is\nused to flip the state from the lower state to\na higher state or vice versa. The π/2-pulse is\nto create an entangled state 1/√2(|1⟩+i|2⟩) from\nstate |1⟩ or |2⟩, or disentangle 1/√2(|1⟩+i|2⟩)\nback to |1⟩ or |2⟩.\n\nThis page shows a simulation that \ndemonstrates the idea based on solving the \ntime-dependent Schrodinger equation for a\nparticle in a potential well, which represents\na solid-state implementation of a qubit. You \ncan turn off the electric field by setting the \n\"eFieldIntensity\" parameter to zero. A list\nof three frequencies are preset for your\nexperimentation (one of them will not trigger\nthe Rabi oscillation because it corresponds\nto a forbidden transition according to the\nselection rule).","decimals":3,"color":"#808080","textColor":"#ffffff","useHtml":false,"keepResult":false},{"name":"x0","uid":"Slider #1729939a127","x":304,"y":151,"width":100,"height":60,"minimum":-10,"maximum":10,"steps":20,"value":-10,"source":true,"snapToTick":true,"valuePrecision":2},{"name":"Series Block","uid":"Series Block #1729939b60f","x":459,"y":274,"width":60,"height":100,"start":-10,"increment":0.2,"count":100},{"name":"dx","uid":"Slider #172993aa70d","x":306,"y":220,"width":100,"height":60,"minimum":0.1,"maximum":0.2,"steps":10,"value":0.2,